TÌ²hÌ²oÌ²uÌ²gÌ²hÌ²tÌ²sÌ²: This is a tough book for me to review. I found the plot very interesting and unique and I enjoyed learning more about out the art world. I like the dual timelines and how the struggles of Anita and Raquel mirrored each other. There were some very intense scenes involving racism and misogyny that will definitely stick with me.

On the other hand, the plot was really slow and drawn out. I wasnâ€™t a total fan of some of the supernatural elements and felt like there either needed to be more or less. I also wish Anita was a more developed character and more relatable. 

Overall this had some good points but also some bad points. I did go down a rabbit hole afterward about the real life artist this book is based on!

OÌ²vÌ²eÌ²rÌ²vÌ²iÌ²eÌ²wÌ²: Anita de Monte, a rising star in the art world, is found dead in New York City; her tragic death is the talk of the town. Until it isnâ€™t. By 1998 Anitaâ€™s name has been all but forgottenâ€”certainly by the time Raquel, a third-year art history student is preparing her final thesis. On College Hill, surrounded by privileged students whose futures are already paved out for them, Raquel feels like an outsider. Anita de Monte is going to be a star. Her art is fantastic, but when she dies at a young age, it seems she is quickly forgotten. Itâ€™s been 13 years and Raquel is an art history student working on her thesis. She doesnâ€™t really fit in with her classmates, a large group of students with a ton of privilege. Being a person of color leaves her feeling like she has to work much harder than her peers. When she starts dating one of those privileged students however, her rank quickly rises. When Raquel comes across Anitaâ€™s work, she starts to see some similarities.

This synopsis does not do this book justice. However, I donâ€™t even know how to write one that does! I just adored this book! Anita was such a fantastic character, and I only fell more in love with her as the book went on (IYKYK.) I also loved Raquel, but as her relationship forced her to make changes to please him, my heart just broke and I wanted to shake her into dumping this dude. I loved the dual timeline and the descriptions of the art world which were unfortunately pretty spot on! This was a unique story that was absolutely excellent on audio! It has a full cast, so I highly recommend listening to this one!

About the Instructor: 

Emma Sheinbaum (@emmasheinbaum) is Co-Founding Editor of the genreless literary journal, A Velvet Giant. Her essays, video-essays/cine-poetry, and poems are published by Milk Press, TriQuarterly, Metatron Press, Juked, Cherub Magazine, The InQueery, and Glass Mountain, among others. Emma also has an essay forthcoming in Cobra Milk. The Poetry Society of New York and The Sundress Academy for the Arts have awarded her writing residencies. She lives in Brooklyn where she likes to hang out with her cat, go bouldering, and make stained glass art

Danielle McClellan reviews ANITA DE MONTE LAUGHS LAST by Xochitl Gonzalez for BookBrowse.
@xochitltheg @flatiron_books

An undergraduate art history student researches the life of a Cuban American artist whose story strangely parallels her own.

In the end, Gonzalez's arrows all hit their targetsâ€”the elite worlds of academia and the fine arts, racism, misogyny, gaslighting, power dynamicsâ€”with a full, furious force. That said, the book is not without its flaws. Powerful convictions can at times turn the baddies into straw men. Several chapters written from Anita's husband's egocentric perspective fell flat for me, although they successfully advance the plot. Overall, this is a rollicking and insightful read, and I heartily recommend it.
-Danielle McClellan, BookBrowse reviewer

by XÃ³chitl Gonzalez

Initially, this felt like a totally unique story that follows a young female artist whose life was lost by the hands of her husband. Everyone around including the art world sweeps this under the rug and continues on. Devastating. 

Iâ€™ve paused on this review for sometime now as I wasnâ€™t sure how I felt, and after digging in more, itâ€™s hard to support this book. This book was inspired by the life of Ana Mendieta, who was not mentioned whatsoever in the pages. 

Itâ€™s unfortunate to hear her family sharing that they were not consulted or reached out to prior to publication. There is great fear in the amount of focus on â€˜ Anitaâ€™sâ€™ death instead of focus on the power of her fierce, engaging, grippingly raw, feminist and unique art. 

I wanted to love this one so much more given the rave reviews I read for it. And although it was entertaining and I found it important to put energy and attention into BIPOC artists that have been silenced it felt a little too chaotic. I will also say that magical realism rarely works for me and here I found it to be just distracting. 

Although I cannot recommend this book now, I will say I was happy to have found and learned about another unknown artist.

{5.25.24} - REVIEW: Crow Talk

This story takes place on a remote lake where two families are trying to escape their problems. The first family have a young boy who has intense mood swings and has stopped speaking. The pressure between his parents as they argue between being supportive and present versus getting a diagnosis is intense. The other person we follow is an adult woman who has just lost her father and is dealing with that grief as well as the rejection of her thesis on her research on birds. The two families meet and begin to connect and it begins to heal them all.

If youâ€™re neurodivergent, you will definitely feel seen in this story. We get two characters who are on different ends of the spectrum and see how they help each other. Iâ€™m not an overly emotional person but this story definitely took me through all of my feelings. It does wrap up with a prettier bow than I anticipated but I think most will like that.

Read this if you liked Bewilderment or Beautyland.

Whatâ€™s the last book that really tugged at your emotions?
